  "output": "This is a pure Python job-scraping pipeline (asyncio + httpx + SQLite) — there's no React/frontend, so that category doesn't apply. Here's what I found across the categories that do:\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the batch, `diff()` issues one `SELECT`, then one `INSERT`/`UPDATE`, each as a separate round trip — classic N+1, just against SQLite instead of a network DB. Boards like Amazon/Microsoft return thousands of rows per run, so this is thousands of serial `cursor.execute()` calls.\n\n```python\n# now: N SELECTs + N INSERT/UPDATEs\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\n**Fix** — batch the lookup, then batch the writes:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):           # stay under SQLite's param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in self.conn.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))       # unchanged: just bump last_seen\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,...,:now,:now)\"\"\",\n                     [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\",\n                     [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27` (`_compile`)\n\n`match()` is called once per job, and it calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside that per-job call** — recompiling the same list of regex patterns from scratch for every single job. `re.compile()` called directly (not via the `re.search(pattern, ...)` module-level shortcut) bypasses Python's internal regex cache, so this really does re-parse every pattern N times for N jobs.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nand change `match()` to accept pre-compiled patterns instead of raw keyword lists, dropping the `_compile()` calls from the hot path entirely.\n\n## 3. Caching opportunity — pagination in `fetchers.py` re-fetches the whole board every run\n\nEvery fetcher with pagination (`fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_apple`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_eightfold`, `fetch_phenom`, `fetch_bytedance`) only stops early when a page returns zero results it hasn't seen *within this run's pagination loop* — it never checks against what's already in the DB. Since most of these APIs sort newest-first and expose real timestamps (`t_create`, `postedTs`, `posted_date`), and the store already tracks a watermark (`meta.last_scan`, read in `agent.py:87`), you're re-downloading the entire multi-thousand-role board every 12h scheduled run even though only a handful of jobs are actually new.\n\n**Fix** — pass the last run's high-water mark into `fetch_all`/fetchers and stop paginating once a page's newest timestamp is older than it:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_amazon(client, source, since: datetime | None = None) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    for pg in range(max_pages):\n        data = await _get_json(...)\n        jobs_raw = (data or {}).get(\"jobs\") or []\n        batch = parse_amazon(company, jobs_raw)\n        if since and batch and all(j.posted_dt and j.posted_dt < since for j in batch):\n            break                      # sorted newest-first — nothing further is new\n        ...\n```\n\nThis turns most runs from ~40 sequential HTTP requests per source into 1-2, which also shrinks wall-clock latency (pagination within a single fetcher is a sequential `for` loop, not concurrent — `fetch_all`'s `asyncio.Semaphore` only parallelizes *across* sources, line 1126-1147).\n\n## 4. Redundant computation — `Job.content_hash` / `Job.posted_dt` (`models.py:60-69`)\n\nBoth are plain `@property`s that recompute (SHA-256 hash, date parsing) on every access. `Store.diff` currently accesses `job.content_hash` once for comparison and `to_row()` recomputes it a second time for any changed/new job. Not hot enough to matter much once #1 is fixed (batch path calls `to_row()` once per job either way), but worth noting: since `Job` is `@dataclass(slots=True)`, you can't use `functools.cached_property` without adding an explicit slot for the cache — if you want to memoize, add `_content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)` as a slot and cache manually.\n\n## 5. Memory leaks\n\nNot really applicable — this is a short-lived CLI/cron script (runs every 12h per the scheduler), not a long-running server. Resource handling is actually solid: `Store` and `httpx.AsyncClient` are both used via context managers / explicit `close()`/`aclose()` in `pipeline.py` and `agent.py`, so connections don't accumulate across runs.\n\n## Bonus: blocking I/O inside async pipeline\n\n`notify.py`'s `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_email`/`notify_sms` use synchronous `httpx.post` and `smtplib`, called from `dispatch()` in `pipeline.py:44`, which itself runs inside the `async def run()`. These block the event loop for the duration of each network call (SMTP handshake, Twilio POST, etc.) — harmless today since nothing else runs concurrently after `fetch_all`, but worth flagging if you ever add concurrent work after dispatch. Switch to `httpx.AsyncClient` + `aiosmtplib` if that changes.\n\n---\n\n**Priority**: #1 (N+1 store writes) and #3 (full board re-fetch every run) are the two with real impact — #3 in particular is likely your dominant cost/latency driver given board sizes (Amazon/Microsoft: thousands of roles, `max_pages=40`). #2 is cheap to fix and strictly correct. #4/leaks are minor/non-issues.\n",
